  <section class="seo-content" style="max-width:720px;margin:0 auto;padding:0 20px 60px;">
    <h2>Click Speed Test — Complete FAQ</h2>

    <h3>What is CPS (Clicks Per Second)?</h3>
    <p>CPS stands for Clicks Per Second — the number of times you click your mouse button in one second. It is the standard measurement for click speed in gaming. A CPS of 6 is average for most gamers, 8–10 is considered fast, and 14+ is exceptional. CPS is particularly important in Minecraft PvP where faster clicking gives a combat advantage.</p>

    <h3>What is a good CPS score?</h3>
    <p>For a 5-second test, here is a general guide: 1–4 CPS is below average, 5–7 CPS is average, 8–10 CPS is fast, 11–13 CPS is very fast, and 14+ CPS is elite. World record CPS scores exceed 20 CPS using specialized techniques. Your "good" score depends on your goals — casual gamers are fine at 6–8 CPS, while competitive PvP players typically aim for 10+.</p>

    <h3>What is the Kohi Click Test?</h3>
    <p>The Kohi Click Test was originally developed for the Kohi Minecraft server, which was one of the first servers to make click speed testing popular in the competitive Minecraft community. The Kohi server required players to demonstrate certain CPS thresholds, making the test famous. While the original Kohi server has since shut down, the Kohi click test name remains widely used. Our <a href="/kohi-click-test">Kohi Click Test</a> replicates the original experience.</p>

    <h3>What is jitter clicking?</h3>
    <p>Jitter clicking is a technique where you tense your arm and wrist muscles to create rapid involuntary muscle contractions, causing your finger to click very quickly. It can achieve 10–15 CPS compared to the average 6–8 CPS of regular clicking. However, jitter clicking can cause strain over time and is not suitable for prolonged sessions. See our <a href="/jitter-click-test">jitter click test</a> for more details and a dedicated test.</p>

    <h3>What is butterfly clicking?</h3>
    <p>Butterfly clicking involves alternating two fingers (index and middle) on the same mouse button to achieve very high CPS — typically 15–25 CPS. It is faster than jitter clicking and less physically demanding, but requires significant coordination practice. Many Minecraft servers have banned butterfly clicking due to its unusually high CPS. Try our <a href="/butterfly-click-test">butterfly click test</a> to measure your butterfly clicking speed.</p>

    <h3>How do I improve my CPS?</h3>
    <p>The most effective ways to improve CPS are: (1) Daily practice for 10–15 minutes using a consistent timer length, (2) Learning jitter or butterfly clicking techniques, (3) Using a gaming mouse with lighter switch actuation, (4) Keeping your hand relaxed — tension reduces speed, (5) Tracking your scores over time to see improvement trends. Most players see improvement within 2–4 weeks of consistent daily practice.</p>

    <h3>Does mouse type affect CPS?</h3>
    <p>Yes — significantly. Gaming mice with optical switches (Razer, SteelSeries) have near-zero debounce delay, allowing faster registered clicks. Regular office mice may have 10–50ms debounce times that physically limit maximum CPS. Switch actuation force also matters — lighter switches (like Cherry MX Speed Silver or optical switches) allow faster clicking than heavier ones.</p>

    <h3>Is click speed testing useful?</h3>
    <p>Click speed testing is useful for: tracking gaming improvement, comparing performance across techniques, checking if new equipment improves click registration, warming up before competitive gaming sessions, and simply as a fun skill challenge. Many competitive Minecraft and PvP game communities use CPS as a baseline skill metric.</p>

    <h3>What is the world record for CPS?</h3>
    <p>The verified world record for clicks per second over a 5-second period is approximately 14–16 CPS using regular clicking, with jitter and butterfly clicking techniques achieving 20+ CPS. However, world records are difficult to verify due to the potential for hardware assistance. Our tests are designed for genuine human clicking performance.</p>

    <h3>Why does my CPS vary between tests?</h3>
    <p>CPS varies naturally between tests due to fatigue, attention level, anticipation, and finger warming. The first test of a session is often slower as muscles aren't warmed up. Peak performance usually occurs on the 3rd–5th attempt. Taking a few practice runs before recording your official score is a common approach. Average your results across multiple tests for a more reliable baseline.</p>
